description.text:

I'm using a 3mm glass bed although I had to lower my nozzles and loosen the springs on the bed all the way to get the bed high enough. It might be worth making a slightly thinner version.   
To adjust the height, you need to raise both pairs of overhanging arms by an equal amount.

title: CNC Z axis for ARDUINO projects ,  PCB drill ,  micro router ...Nema 14 motor

description.text:
ABS slider for small CNC projects ABS body and slider. All others parts are metal. You can find all metal parts local or the kit here: http://www.cnc4newbie.com Price for motor/metal kit is 70$ shipping included for USA and Canada.
USE COUPON CODE : NEMA14SHIP Included in the kit:
-1x Nema 14 motor with wiring harness (only 2 holes are threaded on the motor)
-2x 6" stainless smooth rods 5/16" diameter
-1x 1/4-20 steel screw
-1x 1/4-20 steel nut
-1x aluminum rigid coupling
-1x flange bearing
-6x set-screw 4mm x 5mm
-4x flat head screw 4mm x 16mm
-4x 4mm nut
-4x flat head screw 3mm x 10mm
-3x socket head 4mm x 12mm
-1x aluminum front plate with 7 threaded holes For more instruction go to my instructable: http://www.instructables.com/id/CNC-Z-AXIS-for-ARDUINO-projects-or-small-router-pr/ You need to print the two ABS files.
Print at 0.2mm layer and make attention for not warping the parts.
Print the part on the flat back for better result.
My printer setup: extruder, 210c bead 90c. PLEASE LEAVE A COMMENT IF YOU BUILD ONE OR FEEL FREE TO ASK QUESTIONS ABOUT.

Look the pictures for an image of the assembly process. Step:
1- instasll the 1/4-20 nut in the slider cavity.
2- screw the 1/4-20 long screw in the nut
3- install the coupling with 2 set screws
4- install the flange bearing
5- put the previous assembly in the bearing
6- install the motor with the 4 flat head 3mm screw (use only 2 screws for some motors)
7- insert the 2 stainless rod in the body/slider
8- secure the rods with 4 sets screws (don't over tight) or glue
9-install the front aluminum plate with the 4 nuts
10- voila!!

title: Laser Cutter Mirrors Calibration Jig V2

description.text:
These 3D printed jigs holds piece of paper/card to 2nd and 3rd mirror mounts during CO2 laser cutter beam calibration. No more guessing where hole is or sticky tape mess. These were designed to fit Shenhui Laser SH-G350 (a.k.a. Blue/White 50W eBay laser) mirror mounts. Yours may vary.
Warning: If your mirrors is badly out of alignment laser might strike and burn this jig. Always ware laser safety glasses!
Update: This is update to the original 2nd mirror calibration jig. Now you can calibration both mirrors. Additionally I added "ears" to hold jig to 3rd mirror with rubber band (it was falling off constantly). Handy "hanger" ring now also included.
I also included template for paper/card "target" inserts.
Sketchup files as well as Adobe Illustrator and DWG included.
Update 05/02/2015: Fixed paper target templates. Now includes project file for RDWorks/LaserWorks (calibrated for 50W cutter).
Update 06/30/2015: Here's small tip. No need to remove second piece when replacing paper target. Just lift it slightly and pull/push paper in/out. Can make those targets slightly longer for easier removal.
Let me know if you have any questions in comments.

• Print both holders with ABS or PLA (I used ABS).
  • If your laser cutter works, cut out target inserts from a piece of cardboard/card stock. Cross-hair should be "engraved".
    If your laser cutter is not operation yet, just print these out on regular printer and cut with scissors.
  • Insert card targets into the jigs and snap on your laser's 2nd and 3rd mirrors.
  • User rubber band to hold second jig (just loop it around back of the 3rd mirror holder)
  • Calibrate mirrors as usual.

title: Cube 3D Printer bulk filament spool adapter

description.text:
Update: 3D System has fixed the feature I was exploiting. But now you can purchase an adapter from http://www.cube3dfree.com/
You can still use the adapter and bulk spool holder. The Cube is a solid little printer. It is very simple to use. There are barely any knobs to tweak. Its good for someone that just wants to reliably print things without babysitting the printer. The ABS does have warping issues even with the heated bed. The big problem is the filament razor blade model. The printer is not that expensive, but they charge $49/0.7lbs of filament! (compared to $31/2.2lbs of Octave 1.75mm filament). That is 5X the price! It turns out that you can by-pass/defeat the Dallas Semiconductor 1-wire chip which is located in each cartridge. The chip stores the filament color, remaining amount, etc. This adapter allows you to connect the plastic filament tube and then connect to a spool of generic filament. It was printed on the cube (version 1) 3/22/2016:
I now have a Lulzbot TAZ5. It can use a much larger range of exotic materials (rubber, wood, copper, magnetic iron). I can print large ABS parts and they don't warp. It is much easier to level the bed.

I'm still running experiments to compare the build quality using the Cube filament versus the different less expensive spool filaments. I made a spool holder out of some 1/2 cpvc tubing:
1) three pieces of 6"
2) four pieces of 1"
3) two pieces of 3"
4) six T fittings
5) two 90 degree fittings I hand drilled a hole so you can leave the cartridge filament hanging out. I will update the CAD models when I get the chance.

Rehashed arrosticini for siblings blessed with LASERS! work in progress. Pictures are of v2.0 v2.0: (confirmed working)
5/8" cubes x 6 x 6 x ~5" = 36 skewers v3.0: (untested)

Higher base plate (meat is more centralized to skewer and away from pointy part)
Wider format for proper 1x 'leg o lamb' : 1x full cube Neither require 3D printing anymore, but you could redesign the base plate to be printed and removable for easier extraction.

Laser cut either the v.2 or v3 out of 1/4" acrylic. You will need:
2 of each wall
1 base plate with tabs
1 base plate without tabs
1 top plate (looks like a base plate without tabs but smaller)
(the AI files have extra bits and aren't formatted for click-n-print because every laser cutter is a unique and beautiful snowflake) Form a box and weld them in place (leave the 2nd base plate aside). Once set, drop the 2nd base plate in and weld it in place (if desired, for rigidity)
I welded the acrylic together with this:
http://www.amazon.com/SCIGRIP-10799-Acrylic-Solvent-Water-thin/dp/B00466V8F0/ref=pd_sim_indust_4?ie=UTF8&refRID=09DM66EMQQHMQTBDH6XF (or similar)
and I used 2 base plates welded together, one with tabs for the walls, and another without for rigidity. I used a boneless leg of lamb. For v2.0, one leg was too much meat. It fit (see picture) but I couldn't line up the skewer with the base plate holes because I didn't have any leverage to redirect the tip (2nd picture). This can be fixed by: a) use a metal skewer to poke a pilot hole, b) use less meat (1st picture), c) use a screw head counter-sink bit to chamfer a funnel in the upper base plate.
Cut and butterfly the meat into 1/2"-5/8" thick slices. Layer them into the box. The meat doesn't need to be square, it can fold over on the sides.
Put the upper base plate on top of the meat and begin to drop in skewers. You will need to be as perpendicular as possible and it will require re-positioning the tip to get it in the base plate holes.
Lift the upper plate up a bit and slide a knife down every slot.
Turn it all over and the whole slab should slide out pretty easily.
"Cook until done." I designed v3.0 to fix a), b) and c) above, but to date has not been tested. The meat might be too small at .55", 64 skewers is a lot, I shouldn't have cut out as much fat as I did which would have left enough volume for 2 full runs instead of 2 really small runs, etc.

description.text:
https://youtu.be/g1kqXq96jfY USE NO LESS THAN 5 BODY TUBES TO ENSURE STABLE FLIGHT This is my design for a 24mm rocket, modeled around an Estes D motor.
I've flown two of them (see video), and they both went so high I could not recover them even with 36 inch Mylar streamers instead of a parachute (it was pretty windy). I have a third ready to go, but I'm waiting for a day with less wind to fly it. I also tested one on the ground to make sure the spiral print would survive the ejection charge. I've included the .ork file to be used with Open Rocket if you want to play with the design and test for stability. Please see the instructions section for details about construction!

USE NO LESS THAN 5 BODY TUBES TO ENSURE STABLE FLIGHT All the clearances were setup for ABS plastic. PLA will probably work fine too, but with a looser fit. The nose cone, body tubes, couplers, and launch lugs should all be printed using "spiral vase" mode in Slic3r. A regular layer print may work too, but it's not going to be as smooth / aerodynamic. I assembled the first rocket entirely with light CA (super glue) and the second with 5 min epoxy, the epoxy version seemed to be more ridged and provided a more stable flight. There will be a slight ridge at the base of each tube/coupler from the print bed. You will want to sand that ridge down with a sanding block before assembling, otherwise you'll have a VERY hard time getting the couplers inserted, and an even harder time getting the alignment right. When gluing the body tubes and couplers together make sure to roll the tubes around on a flat surface to ensure that they line up perfectly, if they are misaligned AT ALL rocket will not fly straight. There should be NO WOBBLE when rolling them on a flat surface. On my prints I could not butt them completely together and still get the tubes aligned perfectly, so I also filled in the gaps between the body tubes with epoxy after the initial glue set. Filling in the gaps will improve the aerodynamics and make it stronger. Just put a bead of epoxy on a sheet of paper and roll the body into the bead and then roll it on a clean section of paper to smooth it out. The tip of the nose cone will not fill in completely in spiral vase mode, so you will need to fill it in with a little bit of epoxy. Just drip a glob in from the back and keep rolling it around until the epoxy sets up. I also dabbed a little on the outside and smoothed it out by hand when it began to set up.
The nose cone plug is supposed to be loose in the body tube, you will need to wrap some masking or scotch tape around the plug to achieve desired fitment. The motor is also a loose fit, it will also need a little tape to make it snug, and it should also be taped in place before launch so that it is not ejected with the streamer or chute. The rear of the fins have some extra material. This was added to the design so there would be extra material to sand off with a sanding block to make a nice aerodynamic point on the trailing edge of the fins. The fin alignment jig was designed to be loose on the printed fins because I laminate my fins with printer paper for a better painting surface. If you don't laminate the fins then you will need to wedge some paper or tape around the fins to get a nice snug fit in the jig. There is no difference between the 3 fin files except for the origin offset. That's just how I have my CAD software setup to export the STLs ready to load w/o having to move things around. Same goes for the "24mm Solid Parts" file, it's just the nose plug, shock cord mount, and motor block all in one file ready to go. All you need other than the printed parts to complete the rocket is a shock cord and a Mylar streamer, or parachute. Enjoy!!!

title: Elliptic involute gear cutting with toothed rack

description.text:
!Be sure to always have downloaded the newest version! I was always fascinated by elliptic gears, knowing well that they are not really useful in a practical sense. Some weeks ago I found a gear pump in the internet that was indeed using elliptic gears and after all gained some advantage out of it: http://www.ingo-laemmle.de/Imm.htm Having this application in mind I decided to go a bit deeper into the math of curves and to find out, how to do involute gearing properly on (almost) arbitrary curves in an efficient way. The method I used is a generatlization of the subtractive method I have published previously in my gear cutting project
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:636119
It's in principle applicable to put involute gearing onto any convex shape or body. To describe it in a sentence: Roll a toothed rack with the right amout of theeth along the curve and let it carve out what it touches - just like a real world gear cutting tool. What you get:
  • a nice kinetic object or wall teaser
  • lots of usage examples in the code
  • an easy and well defaulted API
  • neat documented code showing you how that all works
    • What you need:
  • OpenSCAD 2015 (Toothbar uses a dynamic array). It renders much faster
  • ShortCuts.scad library (sorry for that, but it simplifies programming so much). Description in: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:644830
    • Hint: To also do concave curve pieces, my idea would be to roll along their convex inner sides and complement the result. This works well, but needs some fiddling around with piecewise definitions and makes the code cumbersome. Have fun and let me know, how you put it to use.

The best way to use it as a teaser is to print two or more gears and a single bracket for each gear.
Snap the brackets and glue the systems somewhere, where people pass by. I used double faced tape.
This is one of my makes: http://youtu.be/o9NxBw0blQc

title: ASUS MeMo Pad 7 mount on Spektrum DX7s with 3DR radio

description.text: This is based on: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:735065 an awesome design by barneyj. I modified it to fit the Spectrum DX7s and my ASUS MeMo Pad 7. I use this as a GCS with a 3DR radio. The pieces were printed in PLA at .1 mm layer height and 100% density. The center mount piece is tapped with M3 threads. Printed pieces hold threads surprisingly well. M3x12 socket head screws hold the clips to the center piece. An M4x45 flat head screw holds the mount to the transmitter bracket. A nut secures the bolt to one side of the arm. The well in the thumb screw holds an M4 nut. I added a v2 version of the DX7s mount with slightly wider gripping arms. This version sits much more secure on the DX7s. I added a v2 version of the ASUS MeMo Pad mount with a small dimension change to the USB plug compartment. (The cheap eBay USB OTG cables should now fit nicely)
Printed on Ultimaker 2 with 0.1mm layer, 100% infill I used a 5mm brim to hold the parts to the build plate.

title: Custom Folding Landing Gear for the Hovership MHQ2 Quadcopter Frame

description.text:
I love that the MHQ2 has folding arms that make it smaller and easier to pack up.  I thought I'd try my hand at creating some custom landing gear that also can fold up.  
These are designed to use a 3mm diamter screw (probably 20mm long) and also use a foam ear plug (cut in half) at the bottom.  I'll upload a photo once I try it out.

Print two copies of the base, and four legs.  The base should attach to the bottom plate of the Hovership MHQ2 right where the original landing gear would go.  
The rounded face is for LED lights and should be oriented away from the center of the quad.  
The legs should attach and use a 3mm bolt as a hinge pin.  Probably 3mm x 18mm or 3mm x 20mm with a lock nut.   
Also, the "feet" are designed to have a cushion attached.  I plan on using a standard foam earplug.  Cut it in half and use the bottom (smaller) half with a hole cut for the mounting rod.  
If you print it let me know how it works for you! Thanks.

title: Landing gear/Skids for Cheerson CX-20, Quanum Nova quadcopter

description.text: ** Update 4-12-2015 Gimbal version is here - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:768744 If you have one of these, you know the OEM landing gear breaks very easily. Rather than keep epoxying it back or buying new ones, I decided to make up a printable set. In the interest of trying to keep it strong and printing with the grain, I designed it in two pieces, The mount itself is in one piece, but mortises into the landing skids tenons..I made the fit snug to account for different printers, but you can file it down a bit if needed. You can glue it, but I find the snug fit sufficient to keep it in place. Yes, I know the side view looks like a normal front or rear view, but it's the best I can do based on the current design. You'll get used to it! (Update: I added a V2 skid that is curved so that it better represents the forward direction) I printed with PLA at 0.3mm, with 3 shells and 15% fill, and the whole gear weighs in at 59 gms, which is about 15 gms less than the original. Best of all, if it breaks, print another one!

comments.text: This is a very nice landing skid you've done for the CX-20! First of all a big thank you for sharing this. I didn't quite get the reason to make the curve go towards the quad on the front side, i think that is a good idea because of of the camera, so when you use a wide angle the skid is not on the footage. The absolute awesome thing i think you did here is to have gone through the work of making the oval shape where the screws are attached. With that part of the work done, i think many other designs for other landing skids can be made. Yours is perfect for you camera, but I wanted one to use with a gopro gimbal and also where i could attach an iphone 6 too. Do you think that in terms of stability a skid could be done where the legs are independent from each other and are arched to the sides instead of to the front?
comments.author: Downloladers

comments.text: I designed it this way to keep things flat and strong. When you have vertical curves, the layers are not strong in that direction. You are right, a gimbal won't fit in the current design. I am trying a few other things and ideas and will update when I have a working design.
